I stand against the chaos and the cross of holy fire&quot; - N. Peart</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Poobah Goladus</span><br>  Posts: 2548<br> <font color=#333333>(1/3/03 8:56:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=430.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mages and aggro</span><hr size=1> Damage from a pet is attributed almost entirely to the pet.  From what I can tell there is only a very small (one-time?) portion of aggro transferred from pet to you.<br>
<br>
Even supposing Rhion is wrong about the aggro bonus for mages, lets imagine a situation where dps over 75 draws aggro.  (It doesn't work quite like this, but it's close enough for now)<br>
<br>
A rogue hits 76dps and unless he's had a successful evade, he gets aggro.<br>
<br>
A wizard hits 76dps and unless he's used a concussion, he gets aggro.<br>
<br>
A mage pet does 70dps and a mage nukes for 70dps.  Total mage dps is 140.  Since niether the pet or the mage is doing more than 75 dps, the mage isn't getting aggro.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
